<p>Let us explore some mathematical concepts.</p>

<remark>
  <p>
<ul>
  <li><term>Mean</term><idx><h>Mean</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
    AKA 
    <term>Average</term><idx><h>Average</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
    It is one of the most popular way to measure the center of a distribution.
    <me>\overline{x} = \sum\limits_i^n \frac{x_i}{n}</me> 
    It is the sample mean, where <m>x_i</m> represents the <m>i-</m>th observed value.
  </li>
  <li><term>Population mean</term><idx><h>Population mean</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
    and 
    <term>Sample mean</term><idx><h>Sample mean</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
  can be calculated trough the same way, using the 
  <m>\mu = \sum\limits_i^N \frac{x_i}{N}.</m>
  Notice, the population mean is represented by <m>\mu.</m>
</li>
<li>
  <term>Weighted mean.</term><idx><h>Weighted mean</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
  Essentially, mean and weighted mean are same, except that the last one has an impact 
  if the number of observations change.  
    <me>\label{eq:weigthedmeand}
      \text{Weighted mean of } x_i= \frac{\sum\limits_{n}^{i=1} w_i x_i}{\sum\limits_{n}^{i=1} w_i}
    </me>
    where <m>w_i</m>'s are the weights, and <m>x_i</m>'s are the observations.
    Notice the eqs.  and \ref{eq:weigthedmeand} are same if 
    in the last one <m>w_1=w_2=w_3= \dots = w_n = 1</m>
</li>

<li>
  <term>Mode</term><idx><h>Mode.</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
</li>

<li>
  <term>unimodal</term><idx><h>unimodal.</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
</li>

<li>
  <term>bimodal</term><idx><h>bimodal.</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
</li>

<li>
  <term>multimodal</term><idx><h>multimodal.</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
</li>
</ul>
  </p>
  
  </remark>



